# Security Analysis Rules

When working with security-related code in this project or analyzing Laravel applications:

## Run Security Analysis First

Before suggesting security fixes, always gather data:
1. Call `analyze_module` with `module: "security"` to get Laravel-specific vulnerabilities
2. Call `analyze_module` with `module: "owasp"` to get OWASP Top 10 mapping
3. Call `get_issues` with `severity: "CRITICAL"` to prioritize

## OWASP Top 10 (2021) Quick Reference

| Code | Category | Laravel concern |
|------|----------|-----------------|
| A01 | Broken Access Control | Missing `$this->authorize()`, IDOR |
| A02 | Cryptographic Failures | MD5/SHA1, HTTP links, hardcoded secrets |
| A03 | Injection | Raw SQL, system commands with user input |
| A04 | Insecure Design | Missing rate limiting, no input validation |
| A05 | Security Misconfiguration | `APP_DEBUG=true`, wildcard CORS |
| A06 | Vulnerable Components | Wildcard composer versions, missing lock file |
| A07 | Auth Failures | Session fixation, missing MFA |
| A08 | Integrity Failures | Unsafe deserialization, no CI/CD checks |
| A09 | Logging Failures | No security event logging, log injection |
| A10 | SSRF | `Http::get($userInput)` without validation |

## Severity Priority Order

CRITICAL → HIGH → MEDIUM → LOW

Never defer CRITICAL issues. Treat CRITICAL security issues as deployment blockers.

## Score Thresholds for Security

- Security score < 50 → block deployment
- OWASP score < 60 → requires immediate attention
- Any CRITICAL issue → must be fixed before merge
